summary: Former US President Jimmy Carter's extended stay in hospice has challenged perceptions about end-of-life care. At 99 years old, Carter is on track to become the first living president to reach his 100th birthday. Despite shutting down a technology 50 years ago, Congress is considering its revival. In other news, his grandson, Jason Carter, is running for governor of Georgia. Presidential debates have historically influenced elections. Carter's connection to the Allman Brothers Band is highlighted. He and his wife will speak at Georgia Southern University. His grandson confirms his grandfather's resilience despite being near the end of his life. Carter became the longest-living US president five years ago, and a documentary on his relationship with China has been acquired for distribution.
